    content: [
      { type: 'paragraph', data: { text: 'Louis Vuitton does not use serial numbers. Instead, they use date codes — a combination of letters and numbers stamped into the leather that tells you where and when the bag was made. Understanding these codes is one of the most reliable ways to verify an LV piece.' } },
      { type: 'heading', data: { text: 'How to Read a Date Code' } },
      { type: 'paragraph', data: { text: 'From 2007 onward, LV date codes follow a specific format: two letters followed by four numbers. The letters indicate the factory location, and the numbers encode the manufacturing date.' } },
      { type: 'tip', data: { title: 'Decoding the Numbers', description: 'In a code like FL0231: FL = factory (France). The 1st and 3rd digits (02) = week number. The 2nd and 4th digits (31) = year 2031... but wait, that is in the future. This is actually week 23, year 2011. Read: 1st+3rd = week, 2nd+4th = year.' } },
      { type: 'heading', data: { text: 'Factory Codes by Country' } },
      { type: 'paragraph', data: { text: 'France: A0, A1, A2, AA, AH, AN, AR, AS, BA, BJ, BU, CT, DU, ET, FL, LW, MB, MI, MS, NO, RA, RI, SD, SF, SL, SN, SP, SR, TA, TH, TJ, TR, TS, VI, VX. Spain: CA, GI, LO, LB, LM, LW. Italy: BC, BO, CE, FO, MA, NZ, OB, PL, RC, RE, SA, TD. USA: FC, FH, LA, OS, SD.' } },
      { type: 'warning', data: { text: 'A valid date code does not guarantee authenticity. Counterfeiters have gotten good at replicating correct formats. Always verify alongside other authentication markers like stitching quality, canvas alignment, and hardware stamping.' } },
      { type: 'heading', data: { text: 'The Microchip Transition (2021+)' } },
      { type: 'paragraph', data: { text: 'Starting in early 2021, Louis Vuitton began phasing out embossed date codes entirely, replacing them with embedded RFID microchips. By mid-2021, most new production exclusively uses chips. The chip is hidden within the lining and is not visible to the naked eye.' } },
      { type: 'paragraph', data: { text: 'The chip can be scanned with an NFC-capable smartphone, though LV has not released a public app for consumers to read the data. Authorized service centers and professional authenticators can access the chip information.' } },
      { type: 'checklist', data: { items: ['Bags made before 2021: should have a stamped date code', 'Bags made 2021: may have either a date code or microchip', 'Bags made 2022+: microchip only, no stamped date code', 'Vintage bags (pre-1980s): may have no date code at all', 'Date codes are always stamped into leather, never printed on fabric tags'] } },
      { type: 'heading', data: { text: 'Common Date Code Red Flags' } },
      { type: 'paragraph', data: { text: 'Watch out for these issues when examining a date code:' } },
      { type: 'checklist', data: { items: ['Font is inconsistent with LV standards (too thin, too thick, wrong spacing)', 'Code is printed on a fabric tag instead of stamped into leather', 'Factory code letters do not match any known LV factory', 'Date decodes to a date that does not match the bag style release year', 'Stamp is too perfectly clean — authentic stamps often have slight imperfections from the hot stamping process'] } },
      { type: 'tip', data: { title: 'Where to Find It', description: 'Date codes are usually found on a leather tab inside the bag — check interior pockets, behind D-ring tabs, or along the seam near the opening. On small leather goods, check the inner card slot area. You may need a flashlight.' } },
    ],
