    content: [
      { type: 'paragraph', data: { text: 'You are at a meet-up, a pawn shop, or staring at an online listing. You need to make a quick authenticity judgment before committing. These four checks can be done in under a minute and will catch the vast majority of counterfeit Rolexes.' } },
      { type: 'heading', data: { text: '1. The Cyclops Magnification' } },
      { type: 'paragraph', data: { text: 'The magnification lens over the date window (called the Cyclops) on a genuine Rolex magnifies the date 2.5x. The date should appear to fill most of the Cyclops window and be perfectly legible. On fakes, the magnification is typically only 1.5x or less, making the date appear small within the window.' } },
      { type: 'comparison', data: { real: 'Date fills the Cyclops lens. Numbers are crisp and easy to read. The magnification is noticeably strong at 2.5x.', fake: 'Date looks small inside the Cyclops. You have to squint. Magnification is weak, often around 1.5x or even flat glass.' } },
      { type: 'heading', data: { text: '2. The Second Hand Sweep' } },
      { type: 'paragraph', data: { text: 'A genuine Rolex has a mechanical movement that produces a smooth, gliding second hand. It makes approximately 8 ticks per second, creating the illusion of a sweeping motion. If the second hand ticks once per second (like a quartz watch), it is definitively fake — Rolex does not make quartz watches in their current lineup.' } },
      { type: 'tip', data: { title: 'Video Check', description: 'If buying online, ask the seller for a slow-motion video of the second hand. Even in regular video, a genuine Rolex second hand appears to glide. A quartz tick-tick-tick is immediately obvious.' } },
      { type: 'heading', data: { text: '3. The Crown Engraving at 6 O\'Clock' } },
      { type: 'paragraph', data: { text: 'Since 2002, Rolex has laser-etched a tiny crown logo on the crystal at the 6 o\'clock position. It is extremely small and nearly invisible to the naked eye — you typically need a loupe or macro lens to see it. The etching is made up of tiny dots, not a solid line.' } },
      { type: 'warning', data: { text: 'Some high-end superfakes now include this etching. Its presence alone does not guarantee authenticity, but its absence on a post-2002 model is a definite red flag.' } },
      { type: 'heading', data: { text: '4. The Weight Test' } },
      { type: 'paragraph', data: { text: 'Rolex watches are made from solid metals — 904L stainless steel, 18k gold, or platinum. They are noticeably heavier than counterfeits, which often use hollow links or lighter alloys. A genuine stainless steel Submariner weighs approximately 155 grams. If it feels light on your wrist, trust that instinct.' } },
      { type: 'checklist', data: { items: ['Cyclops magnifies date 2.5x — date fills the window', 'Second hand sweeps smoothly, not tick-tick-tick', 'Micro-etched crown at 6 o\'clock (post-2002 models)', 'Substantial weight — feels solid and dense on the wrist'] } },
      { type: 'paragraph', data: { text: 'These four checks are your first line of defense. If a watch passes all four, it warrants deeper inspection. If it fails even one, proceed with extreme caution.' } },
    ],
